text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Lampooning vs. Reinforcing stereotypes%0a:Author: kevinx%0a:Original: [[Articles.AsianAmericanDiscriminationInSouthPark|AsianAmericanDiscriminationInSouthPark]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.NickG|NickG]]%0a:Section: D%0a:Completed: 02.05.2021 - 11:48%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-020937-204390#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:09-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-020937-204390#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0a(warning: language)%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=enOQozXwctc%0a%0aIn the above clip, both Asian characters are voiced by series co-creator Trey Parker. The punchline of these characters is their accents, which cause them to pronounce "city" [cɪti] as "shitty" [ʃɪti]. %0a%0aSouth Park has always been a show that relies on outrage comedy. In most cases, it justifies this by rightfully lampooning antiquated stereotypes such as the "Token Black" character in a show or the depiction Canadians in America. In these examples, South Park subverts expectations to criticize a stereotype -- by explicitly naming a character Token Black to make acknowledge and make fun of the show's early lack of diversity or by animating Canadian characters as anatomically different to Americans to make fun of how Americans see themselves as superior to Canadians.%0a%0aHowever, in the case of depiction of Asian stereotypes, sometimes the show doesn't as much lampoon them as harmfully reinforce them. In the clip in the main article, it could be argued that the show is flipping the script on how white comedians like to mock Asian accents by having Asian comedians mock white people. However, in both clips, the show doesn't make an effort to criticize the fact that Asians are so often mocked for their accent, but instead joins in using the accent as part of the punchline.%0a%0aIn a later episode of South Park, it is revealed that the owner of City Wok is, in fact, a white character who believes himself to be Asian. This backhandedly justifies the use of a stereotypical Asian accent, but it's hard to say if this is the show retconning the character to avoid backlash or genuinely changing its stance.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
